{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.01,0.2,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79688"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11578"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"857"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37066"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-week-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of bilious vomiting. He has been feeding poorly and appears irritable. He was born at term with no complications and has been growing well. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 160/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 45/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft but mildly distended. There is no visible peristalsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 18 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (5-15)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 105 g/L (95-135)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 350 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate: 2.8 mmol/L (0.5-2.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography scan","Upper gastrointestinal contrast study","Magnetic resonance imaging","Plain abdominal radiograph","Abdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with bilious vomiting, which should be considered due to malrotation with midgut volvulus until proven otherwise. This is a surgical emergency that requires prompt diagnosis and treatment to prevent bowel ischaemia and necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper gastrointestinal contrast study\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for suspected malrotation. It can demonstrate the position of the duodenojejunal flexure and any obstruction. The classic finding is a \u0027corkscrew\u0027 or \u0027spiral\u0027 appearance of the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may show the \u0027whirlpool sign\u0027 of volvulus but is operator-dependent and may miss the diagnosis. It is not reliable enough to exclude malrotation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain abdominal radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E may show a \u0027double bubble\u0027 sign but is non-specific and can be normal in early presentations. It cannot reliably diagnose or exclude malrotation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E can demonstrate malrotation but involves radiation exposure and often requires sedation in infants. It is not the first-line investigation when a contrast study can provide the necessary information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this emergency setting due to the time required and need for sedation or anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce malrotation is diagnosed, urgent surgical intervention with a Ladd procedure is required. This involves derotation of the volvulus if present, division of Ladd\u0027s bands, placement of the small bowel on the right and large bowel on the left of the abdomen, and appendicectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bilious vomiting in an infant should be considered due to malrotation with volvulus until proven otherwise.","Upper gastrointestinal contrast study is the gold standard investigation for suspected malrotation.","Urgent surgical intervention is required for malrotation with volvulus to prevent bowel ischaemia."],"references":["Salehi Karlsl\u00e4tt K, Husberg B, Ullberg U, Nordenskj\u00f6ld A, Wester T. Intestinal Malrotation in Children: Clinical Presentation and Outcomes. Eur J Pediatr Surg. 2024 Jun;34(3):228-235. doi: 10.1055/s-0043-1764239. Epub 2023 Mar 7. PMID: 36882104."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T12:58:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T12:59:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"i